Ask HN: How best to take down large (Tether) WFH fraud impersonating businesses?
text:
Our company was recently involved in what we believe is a very large work-from-home Tether fraud. The basic setup of the scam is:

1. Scammer sets up a fraud site with branding/domain name similar to an established company.

Examples: https://adverityuk.com, https://applifyrevue.com

2. These sites are used to recruit victims for a work-from-home scam and ultimately involve them buying/transferring Tether.

3. The legitimate company receives complaints when the victim tries to complain or get their money back ultimately damaging the brand/business of the company.

We're unsure of the scope of this scam but we believe it's very large as we interviewed victims that lost from USD$15-50K. You can see a warning about this scam at: https://fenzodigital.com/.

Many of the scam sites have a reverse IP of 20.232.140.198 and you can see a small sample of the +1000 domains we're aware of at: https://pastebin.com/1tbqtfPi.

We believe the host resolves to a CDN based in China (https://www.dnsqx.com/gfcdn.html) that is hosted on Azure.

We've:

* Contacted the Registrar (Name.com) but they basically said we need to contact the host or work through ICANN.

* Submitted a complaint to the domain registrant through Name.com (no response yet)

* Submitted a complaint to Azure (no response yet)

* Tried contacting the CDN through Telegram (no response yet)

Are there any other suggestions for bringing down this scam ASAP?

Ask HN: Can a single LLC offer multiple unrelated services?
text:
Kind of a general question to pose to the HN sphere:

Let's say I own a coffee shop (as an LLC) and sell coffee and snacks. What if I want to start offering "Coffee Shop Consulting Services" for other coffee shop owners or something that's kind of unrelated to the original business. Is this a relevant thing to do under a single LLC? If this is tolerable or normal - at what point should a separate business be created for two/multiple business pursuits?

Thoughts or anything is appreciated, thanks.

Ask HN: Has anyone started an IaaS after working only at large tech companies?
text:
I work on an infrastructure team at Meta. I love large distributed systems work and like the sort of work I do, but I’m getting a bit ground down by the machine.

I had a thought about how I’d love to try to solve some infrastructure and scaling issues as a general service - I’m not sure what that would look like, but perhaps some sort of IaaS.

My problem is I have no idea how to discover what that would look like. I have very little experience outside of large tech companies, which means I have no idea what sorts of needs exist in the market.

I’d love to try to learn a bit more about what people and companies need, but I don’t know how. If you’ve mainly worked in tech and wound up building services as a product later in your career, how did that journey go for you?
